spanGrp.span: `What are the words that we used in our everyday conversations at home which are not anymore use now?.'
ki-yi de ki-kyntein ki wa pynmkam ha yung ha sm ki wa boon hi katni ym tip de ki?

`the things that are unknown nowadays are 'duli', then the front part of the house is called 'dhari' (front veranda) so what does it means by 'dhari' ? whatever talks or discussions we have, the elders of the 'dorbar ri' have they will do it in the 'dhari', this is 'tre thlong but here is the 'chloor', 'chloor' was called 'rkut' from 'rkut' to 'kyndur' from 'kyndur' to 'lakyndur.'

ki wa ym tip de katni t ka-duli, ki-kamra ong ki ka nong myntu ka-te hakhmat hei-te ong i ka ka-dhari yi mut dhari? ka wa chong pyrkhat ka-dorbar ri, i-won i-won wa yaklam pyrkhat toh ha dhari u-ya-pyrkhat ki wahh dorbar ri, tre thlong mut ka-ni toh ka-tre thlong, t poi yn hei-ni yn t ong ki ka ka-chloor, ka-chloor ong i ka ka-rkut, na rkut kyndur, na kyndur poi lakyndur.

`these are six main parts (of a house), so right now we are sitting in the 'tre thlong ('tre'literally means the bottom and 'thlong means 'a mortar')and it does not mean the place where the mortar is kept, 'tre thlong means a place where the roots of any talks is being held.'

ynru tylli ki-t ki-main mut kamwa ong i-chong hei-ni t mut yn i-chong ha tre thlong, ym toh sa mut tre thlong i-thaw booh thlong, hynrei tre thlong mut ka wa chong kawon kawon ka-bynta ha tre mut ka-tre ka wa yaklam i ye-i-won yei-won.
`now it is known as the living room but its original name was 'tre thlong and these were Ynniaw wasa's words.'
Katni ong ki ka-kamra chong ke ka-pyrtuit yong ka toh tre thlong, ki-t toh ki-kyntein Ynniaw wasa

`before we get into the house we enter the 'dhari' first after then comes the 'tre thlong', after tre thlong then the 'chloor' after 'chloor' then the 'rkut' which is a kitchen (these are room patterns in our state).'
i-yung cht ja t i-yoo mi katni wan i ynne na dhari nong, poi ha tre thlong t poi ha chloor nong, na chloor t poi yn i ha ka ka-ni ka wa ha yung chtja t ong i ka ka-rkut, rkut toh ka-yung chtja.
`so kyndur is a room where the drinking water (in a pot) was kept, 'palat kyndur was another room for keeping the farming instrument like spade and anything that can be hanged.'
t kyndur ka-kyndur toh wa booh um bih yi, ka-palat kyndur yn ka wa booh wakhu ka-booh tiar ya ki-won ki-won ki-t ki wa wah ki s, t toh i-bynta
` but in the religion there are so many things, during rituals there are things we focused like 'u syngkhien u pyrda', 'ha yung ha sem'..'

T m yn man ha ka-niam wan boonjait ki yoo phi, ha ki-bynta yong ka-niam wan nong myntu ha ka-ni ka-tynne ka wa hawa chat wa khen hei-ni m ka-bynta lh boonjait, ha ka-ni m ka-t ka-bynta ka wa man da pyn-chong i n. u-syngkhein u-pyrda, ha yung ha sm

`when the egg was kept in its place during rituals and after the citation of rites during the ceremony, the egg was taken and was given a bath, Ynniaw wasa's words said 'i mynthoo mynnu, wa ben ne wa khoh, lana lahon, thoh dawsoo daw hiem, ya u-tip chynrang kynthai ya u-tip yei-lieh yei-looh".( this ritual is maybe for a particular ceremony like they have different rituals for different ceremonies, cross check).'

T ki-ni m ki-bynta ki manda pyn-chong i ya ka-pylln nong t manda dp ki-niaw ki-tang waroh u-chim ya ka-tu u-pyn-sum pyn-sait i ka ya ka-pyllen, i-kyntein u-ynniaw wasa ong "i mynthoo mynnu, wa ben ne wa khoh, lana lahon, thoh daw soo daw hiam, ya u-tip chynrang kynthai ya u-tip yei-leit yei-loid".
`many of the words, so mynthoo mynnu, we ben wa khoh, these are Ynniaw wasa words that many would not understand nowadays, so mynthoo mynnu means who creates us, who spits and clean

Kamt lh mut katni ktein boon, t mynthoo mynnu, wa ben ne wa khoh, t mut katni ki-ktein ki-t toh ki-ktein Ynniaw wasa boon ki wa ym sniawthooh ki ki-t kyntein, t mynthoo mynnu t mut mynthoo mynnu t mut i wan thoo s t mut yi wa mynthu wa khaat s

`wa ben means to speak ill about someone, wa khoh (khoh means to peel or a cone shape basket) means to tell everyone the makeup story [wa khanatang (makeup story)] about somebody, so these are Ynniaw wasa's words.'

Mynthoo mynnu wa ben mynnu t mut wa klam ben klam roi n, wa khoh wa khoh wan t mut man da ong i-ktein khoh wa ben mynnu wa khoh, wa khoh t mut wa khanatang, khoh t mut khana ki-t toh ki-kyntein Ynniaw wasa

`there are other wasa's words like 'i snoom, snoom lariang phariang', what is this lariang phariang, lariang phariang means the spring water which came out of a certain source, this water like substance showed who collected who took it, that's the lariang phariang.'

m wan ha ki-kyntein Ynniaw wasa ong i i wa ong i-snoom, snoom lariang-phariang, ka-yi ka ka-t ka-lariang-phariang, ka-lariang-phariang t mut toh ka-t ka-um ka wa mih na changpt na changpar, ka wa man um ka-lariang-phariang toh ka wa ri ka wa pyn-yoo ka wa khaat wa kyndup ka wa m ha ka-changpt changpar ka-t toh ka-lariang-phariang ka-t toh i-pyrtuit ko

`in the present generation there are many who don't understand and don't know about what is this lariang phariang, if i say what is water they will certainly know it, and what is a spring, some of them knew.'
T mut ha ki-ni ki-patein katni ki wa boon ym sniawthooh ki ka, la ong o ka-yi ka ka-lariang-phariang, ym tip ki, t ong o ka-yi ka ka-um t tip hi ki, ong ka-yi ka ka-changpt, changpt lh m hi watip.

`these are something, our language will slowly die why? Because the present generation don't use these anymore and they are speaking the so to say market (broken pnar or not a pure one) language (just like bazaar hindi).'
ki-t ki-bynta ki wa i man ka-patein katni i-ktein yong i toh suki suki u-dooh i, ilh dooh i wa da yaklam yong yaw h, t myllin i-t.

`the third one is, you should understand, when i say 'wa kna wa khriam (to perform rituals), to kna even you can do but you cannot 'khriam', khriam is something that comes from the mouth words should come from the mouth.'

ka wa le yn ka wa myntu yoo mi, i-won i-won bynta toh u-sniawthooh i, myntu ong i wa kna wa khriam, u-kna yee hi mi ne u-chong hei-tu ne hynrei wa ym yee wan mi u-khriam, ka-khriam man ko ka wa mih, ym yei-mi u-sniawthooh wa mih na ktein, naktein mi u-khriam.

`you know how to 'kna but you don't know how to 'khriam', you know how to write but you don't know how to tear, (in khasi and pnar we have the echo word 'ka-thoh ka-tar which means literature but separately thoh means write and tar means to tear), you know how to 'thmat but you don't know how to 'trong and the same thing happened to all the people.'

Tip mi u-kna s tang wa ym tip mi u-khriam, tip hi mi u-thoh s tang ym tip mi u-taar, ka-ni ka wa ong i kamni yn n, tip mi u-thmat tang ym tip mi u-trong, waroh ki-bru toh tip hi ki u-thmat s tang ym tip ki u-trong.
`you know how to 'khen (to count) but you don't know how to 'khaai (cross check), and these are parts of our culture that we the present generation really don't understand.'
Tip hi u-khen tang ym tip u-khaai, u-khen tip hi s u-khen tang wa u-khaai ym tip mi mut ka-t ka-rukom wan ka-jingyaphr ka wa man ka wa i tang ki-paten wa katni ym m u-paiphang ya ki-t ki-bynta.

`these are the things which needed deep concentration so as to understand, there are two things to be concentrated, when we say 'sla (leaf) we also say 'tloor ( ), when we say 'lmet (a different kind of leaf) we also 'ladaw (banana), if we say 'soiong (a kind of fruit here, black skin, marble size, flesh is maroon in color) we also say 'sotew (this is another different kind but i think it came from the same family with the latter), if we say 'siej (bamboo) we also have to say 'chken' (bamboo)." Note: i don't know how to differentiate this but i can just say both 'siej and 'chken are bamboo, siej is word use in khasi and ckhen in pnar..'

ki-t toh ki-bynta ki wa man i-kam ki-bru toh ya u-ngam yillu i ya u-sniawthooh i, i-won i-won i-bynta, m ha ki-won ki-won ki-bynta arjait wa m ong i ka-sla ong i ka ka-tloor, ong i ka-lmt ong i ka-ladaw, la ong wan i u-sooyong ong i u-sootew, la ong i ka-siej ong i ka-chkn mut ar ar jait m ki.

`to find out the truth there has to be an indepth concentration, all of us knew that there is a huge tree, but who holds the tree so that it can stand? There are roots that support the tree but we can't see them and the roots sucked the nutrients for the tree to grow bigger.'

Man hei-t u-ngam ya u-sniawthooh mi ka-yi ka ka-nongrim myntu to ya u-chm mi yei-jingsakhiat, man waroh toh tip i watoh m u-dein bah u-dein bah m u wa hh bha, t yi wa ksoh ya utu? m wan ki-thied, ki-thied ym yoh i ki u-yoo, ki-t toh ki-bynta ki wa ki-tai ki-thied ki wa tan wan yei-bam ya u-pynhh ya u-dein bah.

`now when we worship God, we worship Him but we cannot see him, we worship Him to give us blessings, and what is that? so the same thing with the tree, it grew bigger because of the nutrients from the roots but we cannot see them.'

myntu hawa ngooh Blai i, ngooh i ya u-blai s, t tang ym yoh i oo u-yoo, ngooh i ya u-e u ya i ki-jingkyrkhu ka-t ka-yi ka? T kamtu u-dein lh ijooh hi, u-dein da pyn-hh ya oo na ki-tai ki-thied ki-tre yong oo ym yoo i ki, na ki-tai pynhh u-dein.

`so our philosophy, theology is very vast and deep, if we do not go deep into it from the bottom it will be very difficult to find out the truth, these are parts to be understood to find out the valuable things in life.'

t ka-filosophy, theology yong i toh man jngai ko s, la da ym ngam ym che la da ym ngam yillu i ka-t mut la ym ngam i chatre t t mut ym chm i ki-jingsakhiat, ki-t toh ki-bynta ki wa kammon u-sniawthooh kammon u-chmphang i-bynta i wa kordor toh u-thooh s.
